result.execSummary:
The defendant Debradre Damon Jackson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Debradre Damon Jackson is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges. On one or more other charges, Debradre Damon Jackson was found not guilty. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Debradre Damon Jackson is presumed innocent of the not guilty charges.

  • Debradre Damon Jackson was found guilty of Substantial Battery-Intend Bodily Harm [Modifiers: Repeater], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Debradre Damon Jackson in court.  Michael Christopher Schindhelm appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Deputy Court Clerk: rmm.  
For reasons stated on the record, Court denied defense motion for mistrial and defense motion for reconsideration.  Court took judicial notice of certified documents regarding case #* that are attached to the complaint and defendant is a repeater.  Court struck the domestic abuse enhancer.  Court found the state has satisfied victims' rights law.  Statements by each counsel and defendant as to sentencing.  Court sentenced defendant to serve a Term of Imprisonment of 5 YEARS in the Wisconsin State Prison, consecutive to any other sentence; credit for 157 days served.  Court ordered 3 YEARS Initial Term Of Confinement and 2 YEARS Extended Supervision.
Court found defendant not eligible for Challenge Incarceration or Earned Release Programs.

Conditions of Extended Supervision:
- No further violations of the law.
- Complete batterer's intervention program.
- Mental health evaluation; take all prescribed medications.
- AODA assessment; comply with any treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety; random urine screens.
- Attend treatment and/or counseling as determined.
- No contact with victim while in custody or on exended supervision.
- Obtain/maintain employment or attend school.
- No contact with firearms.
- Pay all costs, surcharges and supervision fees.  The Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.
